INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - NIGHT

Dark. The launch complex lit below the glass. Hale at the desk, tie gone, the phone in his hand.

He types two words. Looks at them.

INSERT — THE PHONE: Look up.

He posts it, and sets the phone face down on the desk.

INT. ROY'S DINER - NIGHT

The phone behind the register buzzes. Earlene reads it. Shows the Cook.

EXT. DAWES FARMHOUSE - NIGHT

The yard dark. The porch light comes on.

Off. On. Off — on, on.

DANNY on the porch, hand on the switch, working it: two — pause — two. Two — pause — two. He's been staying out at the farm since his father left.

EXT. RIDGE ROAD - NIGHT

Joss's truck headlights answer across the dark section land: two — two. Joss stands up in the bed and watches farmhouse after farmhouse come alight down the valley — porch lights snapping on, some steady, some flashing, spreading fence line to fence line.

EXT. PIONEER FIELD, BALLPARK - NIGHT

Empty stands. The GROUNDSKEEPER at the breaker panel throws the light towers on — off — on, whole banks at a time, the field strobing under them.

EXT. AMERICA - NIGHT (AERIAL)

Suburb grids pulse. A skyline flickers block by block. Highways run bright with flashers. The dark country between cities fills with pinpoints, porch by porch, until the whole country is lit.

INT. REGIONAL GRID CONTROL ROOM - NIGHT

A wall of monitors, load curves spiking hard off the top of the chart. A GRID OPERATOR stares at it, headset on.

GRID OPERATOR:
(into headset, disbelieving)
That's more draw than the whole state used to pull on the Fourth. Every firework stand lit at once. Where's this even coming from?

INT. ROY'S DINER - CONTINUOUS

Buck watches his own porch light blink through the window. Doesn't look away from it.

BUCK:
(to nobody, satisfied)
Good.

EXT. TRANQUILITY BASE - CONTINUOUS

The card game. Stitch, holding his hand of cards, has looked up, past the flags, at the Earth hanging in the black.

STITCH:
Y'all.

They look up. The four olds. Then Brandt. Then Lindqvist. Then Shen.

The night side of the Earth is flickering. Waves of light crawl across it — coastlines pulsing, whole seaboards going bright and dark and bright.

Seven visors tilt back, the Earth small and bright in every one of them.

Nobody says anything for a long time. The cards hang in Stitch's glove, forgotten.

At the grill, without looking away from the Earth, Gunny reaches over and turns down the burner.

CUT TO:
